snippet: The cabinet, which was praised by some for its diversity, replaces the government of Mohamed Morsi, a Brotherhood member who was deposed nearly two weeks ago.
abstract: Gen Abdul-Fattah el-Sisi, Egypt's interim president, swears in new cabinet dominated by liberal and leftist politicians, sweeping away brief era of Islamist political rule built by deposed president Mohamed Morsi; composition of cabinet exposes it to same criticisms once heaped on Morsi, that he excluded his opponents from governing, preventing and sense of political consensus.

byline.contributor: Mayy El Sheikh, Asmaa Al Zohairy and Sarah Mousa contributed reporting.

lead_paragraph: The cabinet, which was praised by some for its diversity, replaces the government of Mohamed Morsi, a Brotherhood member who was deposed nearly two weeks ago.

headline.main: Egypt’s New Government Doesn’t Include Muslim Brotherhood
headline.print_headline: For Egypt’s New Cabinet, Same Complaints as Old One
